      <p align=3D"left"><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size=3D=
"2">We=20
          have tried to be accurate with the above table but cannot     =20
   be held responsible for in-accuracies. <br>
            Go back to first principals and double check your calculations
          if the result is 'mission critical'. <br>
            Even the brilliant brains at NASA have made a conversion   =20
     error or two ! <br>
            <br>
            <font color=3D"#ff0000">The scientific notation</font> used in
the           factors column helps to reduce long numbers to a manageable
         width. E+01 means moving the decimal point one space to       =20
 the right so 1.00E+01 is shorthand for 10, then 1.33E+00          stays
at 1.33 and 1.33E-01 becomes 0.133. The format tends          to be used
when the figure gets longer so E+09 or E-09          cuts out a lot of noug=
hts.<br>
            <br>
            Example:-<br>
            Task: How many sq.rods in 10 acres.<br>
            From the tables: 1 acre =3D 160 sq.rods, so<br>
            </font><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size=3D"2"> =
=20
       10 acres x 160 =3D 1600 sq.rods <br>
            When you want to reverse the conversion, <br>
            divide by the factor viz. <br>
            1600 sq.rods/160 =3D 10 acres<a name=3D"remember"></a><br>
            <br>
            Remember that you cannot create energy only convert it.    =20
    Likewise, you will not find a conversion from pounds to          metres=
=20
 - the basic units must remain the same - mass converted          to mass,=
=20
 length converted to length, et al.<br>
            <br>
            You won't usually find a conversion from kilograms to      =20
  grams - the prefix 'kilo' means '1,000' so a kilogram          is in fact
 1,000 grams in the same way as a kilometer          is 1,000 metres [or
about  1,000 yards in 'old money'].          I have put a few in the table
because  visitors have asked          for them. More prefixes can be found
on <a href=3D"https://lambda.gsfc.nasa.gov/product/websites/AMI/mrao.cam.ac=
.uk/~rob/SI/siprefix.htm">another          table</a>. <br>
            <br>
            One handy metric link between units to remember is that    =20
    1 Litre [1000cc] of pure water weighs 1 kilogram. <br>
            <br>
            If accuracy is critical beware of old versions of MS Excel =20
       which had problems rounding off numbers.<br>
            <br>
            Metrication is a great help but has also created anomalies;=20
        I have seen pressure gauges changed from a commonly used       =20
 psi  to kg/cm.sq., bar, pascal, kPa and atmos but will          no doubt=
=20
move to a popular metric standard in a few decades.</font></p>
